That’s a sentiment many people express when they’ve reached the limits of what they can control.

You could phrase it in a few different ways depending on the tone you’re after:

Sometimes you just have to get out of the way and trust God to do the rest.

Or, a bit more reflective:

Do what is yours to do. Then step aside and trust God with what isn’t yours to carry.

Or, more concise:

Faith is knowing when effort ends and trust begins.

It also reflects a practical distinction that appears in many religious and philosophical traditions: act wholeheartedly on what is within your responsibility, while accepting that outcomes are not entirely yours to command. That isn’t passivity—it’s recognizing the boundary between your agency and what lies beyond it.

In that sense, “getting out of the way” can mean letting go of the urge to control everything, while still showing up fully for the part that’s yours to do.